-- PRESS DIGEST - Hong Kong - July 24
-- By Donny Kwok
-- Wed Jul 23, 2014 09:56PM EDT
-- None



HONG KONG, July 24 (Reuters) - These are some of the leading stories in Hong Kong newspapers on Thursday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST  -- Five Hong Kong pro-democracy lawmakers accused of secretly accepting millions of dollars in donations from media mogul Jimmy Lai Chee-ying may face official investigation. A Beijing-loyalist group has asked the Legislative Council's committee on members' interests to look into the matter. (http://bit.ly/1A89AD4) -- The sale of the fourth batch of inflation-linked bonds worth HK$10 billion ($1.29 billion) attracted hundreds of thousands of investors. A new trend emerged this year with more investors buying the iBonds online, said Gary Leung Wai-kei of Bank of China. (http://bit.ly/1pcUiEm) -- The Housing Authority in Hong Kong may "for a short period of time" fail to keep the average waiting time for public rental housing within three years. The authority revealed that the 8,900 new flats available this year would fall short of the government's construction target of an average 15,000 annually. (http://bit.ly/1rviIh1)THE STANDARD -- Former Hospital Authority chairman Anthony Wu Ting-yuk has been suspended for two years by the Hong Kong Institute of Certified Public Accountants and fined HK$250,000 ($32,300) for professional misconduct. The penalty came 17 years after the liquidation of a company. (http://bit.ly/1rCpi6R) -- The outlook for Hong Kong's banking sector is cloudy due to increasing regulatory costs, says the latest report from global accounting firm KPMG. It said regulatory pressure may require banks to allocate more resources to frontline and supporting functions, adding to operating costs. (http://bit.ly/1qB59P5)  HONG KONG ECONOMIC JOURNAL  -- Chinese power distributor Huadian Power International Corp Ltd <1071.HK> <600027.SS> said it would sell 286.2 million H-shares at HK$4.92 each in a share sale, raising HK$1.41 billion ($181.92 million) for general working capital.   HONG KONG ECONOMIC TIMES  -- Hongkong Airlines is set to launch its initial public offering in the city in October, raising $500 million, according to market sources.